{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"cc8df2de-8716-4bec-88eb-a057aea1b095","content":"I'd be happy to help, but I should clarify: **CLR activation logs are not the right tool for diagnosing a NullReferenceException.**\n\nCLR activation logs (produced by `mscoree.dll`) only cover **runtime selection and loading** — e.g., which CLR version the shim picks, whether the correct framework was found, or if a Features-on-Demand dialog appeared. They don't contain any information about application-level exceptions like `NullReferenceException`.\n\n**For a NullReferenceException**, you'd want to use:\n\n1. **Debugger** — attach Visual Studio or `dotnet-dump` to inspect the call stack and identify the null reference.\n2. **Stack trace** — check the exception's stack trace in your app's output/logs to find the exact line.\n3. **Event Viewer** (Windows) — look under Application logs for the crash details.\n4. **`dotnet-dump collect`** — capture a crash dump for post-mortem analysis.\n\nIf you'd like, I can:\n- Help you **set up crash dump collection** for your .NET app\n- Help you **analyze a stack trace** if you paste it here\n- Invoke the **CLR activation debugging** skill if you suspect the *wrong runtime is being loaded* (a different problem than NRE)\n\nWhich would be most helpful?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b5e957fb-8906-4c5d-9c6d-4b05100c577a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking me to analyze CLR activation logs to diagnose a NullReferenceException in their .NET app. They mentioned CLR activation logs specifically. I have a skill called \"clr-activation-debugging\" that is designed for exactly this purpose - diagnosing .NET Framework CLR activation issues using CLR activation logs.\n\nLet me invoke that skill.","outputTokens":404},"id":"e72aff43-5a3c-4825-9e9d-3e8bdc23bc5e","timestamp":"2026-04-08T01:16:36.059Z","parentId":"70393b0c-7531-435c-97a4-fe12a7b58206"}
